1
00:00:00,233 --> 00:00:17,533
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sama Sambodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sama Sambodassam

2
00:00:17,902 --> 00:00:26,359
Namo Tassa, Bhagavato, Harahato, Sama, Sambuddha, Sam.

3
00:00:26,899 --> 00:00:33,512
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:33,533 --> 00:00:37,261
Now I'm going to talk about things that I know virtually nothing about.

5
00:00:38,563 --> 00:00:39,505
That's a good start.

6
00:00:42,049 --> 00:00:46,256
Really just trying to see what some people say are the gates.

7
00:00:46,817 --> 00:00:52,524
I prefer the sort of avenues down which Buddhism enters into our society.

8
00:00:53,165 --> 00:01:04,462
And you can't help but filtrate out what you don't want and see the Buddha Dharma from a particular point because that's the way we're conditioned.

9
00:01:04,796 --> 00:01:20,638
So, for instance, when Buddhism went to China, it became seen through Taoism, and it took quite a long time for there to realise that Buddhism wasn't quite the same as Taoism, although there were obviously connections.

10
00:01:20,778 --> 00:01:21,659
And it's the same with us.

11
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:31,192
There are obvious connections, but in a sense it can obscure, you might say, the fundamental teachings of the Buddha.

12
00:01:31,510 --> 00:01:34,635
So there are three areas that I'm going to try and point that out to.

13
00:01:34,656 --> 00:01:36,159
The first one is science.

14
00:01:36,900 --> 00:01:38,504
The second one is romanticism.

15
00:01:39,266 --> 00:01:41,049
And the third one is psychotherapy.

16
00:01:42,513 --> 00:01:44,055
There's no psychotherapists in the room.

17
00:01:44,075 --> 00:01:45,358
Oh, no, good.

18
00:01:46,561 --> 00:01:48,584
So the first one is about science.

19
00:01:48,605 --> 00:01:50,007
So...

20
00:01:51,287 --> 00:02:02,102
We have to make a distinction between science, which is the exploration of our physical world, from scientism, which is the philosophy that's drawn from that.

21
00:02:02,862 --> 00:02:13,937
And these days, scientific materialism is really what takes over most people who are involved in science.

22
00:02:13,917 --> 00:02:19,020
Rupert Sheldrake, whom some of you might know, has just written a book about spiritual practices.

23
00:02:19,681 --> 00:02:26,768
And he was saying that it was rare to get a group of scientists as such who weren't materialists.

24
00:02:29,631 --> 00:02:34,754
One of the leading persons is the biologist Wilson.

25
00:02:35,436 --> 00:02:43,823
He's famed for starting a whole new discipline on the social behavior of animals and humans.

26
00:02:44,814 --> 00:02:47,498
the biological aspects of social behavior.

27
00:02:48,159 --> 00:02:51,945
And he wrote a book called Consilience, which means the unity of knowledge.

28
00:02:52,387 --> 00:02:54,409
Underneath it, there's a title, Unity of Knowledge.

29
00:02:54,751 --> 00:02:59,979
It's where all knowledge comes together and forms some sort of whole concept.

30
00:03:00,920 --> 00:03:02,102
And this is what he says.

31
00:03:02,122 --> 00:03:04,967
He says,

32
00:03:04,947 --> 00:03:18,759
from the birth of stars to the workings of social institutions, are based on material processes that are ultimately reducible, however long and tortuous the sequence to the laws of physics.

33
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:27,627
So when you're looking, shall we say, upwards, the first thing you see is physics, you know, if you were to create a hierarchy.

34
00:03:28,269 --> 00:03:31,831
If you're looking up, then obviously it's about stones, it's about

35
00:03:32,064 --> 00:03:33,687
It's about the physics of life.

36
00:03:33,707 --> 00:03:40,457
And then from that you get the chemistry, from that you get the biology, then you get the psychology, sociology, and so on.

37
00:03:40,799 --> 00:03:45,986
So everything looks as though it's all arisen from this physical base.

38
00:03:47,008 --> 00:03:49,793
And that's what he's basically saying.

39
00:03:49,812 --> 00:03:55,322
Interestingly enough, he remains an agnostic as to whether God exists or not.

40
00:03:56,415 --> 00:04:02,310
So that's the basic reductionism of scientism.

41
00:04:03,032 --> 00:04:08,463
And one book that I read which was helpful was Scientism, A Word We Need.

42
00:04:08,645 --> 00:04:11,913
It's by a man called Crowburn and he's written it for people like me who know nothing.

43
00:04:12,514 --> 00:04:13,817
So it was quite enlightening.

44
00:04:14,556 --> 00:04:17,461
of the books that I read became a little bit too technical.

45
00:04:18,401 --> 00:04:28,958
I mean, there's lots of stuff on the website, if you care to look it up, of criticisms, you know, academic criticisms of scientism.

46
00:04:28,978 --> 00:04:35,045
There's one book, I think it cost £75, I didn't go for that one, which is a collection of essays by people.

47
00:04:37,829 --> 00:04:40,132
So here we have a couple of problems that have arisen.

48
00:04:40,374 --> 00:04:42,656
The first one is...

49
00:04:42,855 --> 00:05:05,468
There's no way of finding out, there's no way they can tell how the objective physical world of chemicals and neurons and all those things that we can test translates into the subjective world that we actually experience in terms of emotions, images, moods, sensations.

50
00:05:06,269 --> 00:05:12,237
And there's a special word for those things, they're called qualia, or as we want to understand it, phenomenal experiences.

51
00:05:13,298 --> 00:05:20,428
And there's no understanding as to how the flow of consciousness arises out of that base.

52
00:05:21,350 --> 00:05:22,451
So it's a presumption.

53
00:05:22,673 --> 00:05:28,622
It's a presumption that everything we experience internally is arising out of matter.

54
00:05:30,285 --> 00:05:34,951
That's not, of course, the tradition of all the...

55
00:05:35,302 --> 00:05:36,345
Spiritual traditions.

56
00:05:36,365 --> 00:05:38,987
That's not what all the spiritual traditions are saying.

57
00:05:39,649 --> 00:05:43,815
All spiritual traditions tell us that the mind is something separate, is something other.

58
00:05:45,057 --> 00:05:57,074
In Buddhism, it's something other, but of course, still falls under the three characteristics of, well, the main two of impermanent and insubstantial, not self.

59
00:05:58,776 --> 00:06:13,077
If you want to read it, there's a great essay by Professor Nagel, the philosopher, in which he tries to point this out by the question, what does it feel like to be a bat?

60
00:06:15,141 --> 00:06:18,687
Now, a bat sees things through hearing.

61
00:06:18,706 --> 00:06:23,434
It can actually tell what insect it's going for and whether to eat it or not.

62
00:06:24,088 --> 00:06:24,990
through sound.

63
00:06:25,091 --> 00:06:27,134
It's quite remarkable, the sensitivity of it.

64
00:06:27,814 --> 00:06:40,697
And what he's saying is that it's impossible for him ever to know what it feels like to be a bat because the inner experience is so different from the way that we experience things.

65
00:06:41,790 --> 00:06:47,137
Now, all this has brought about a sort of rethink about the whole problem.

66
00:06:47,177 --> 00:06:54,165
So on the one side, you'll get philosophers and scientists who talk about this reductionism.

67
00:06:54,264 --> 00:06:59,011
Everything will eventually be proven to arise out of subatomic particles.

68
00:06:59,690 --> 00:07:02,113
But there are people who are beginning to question that.

69
00:07:02,134 --> 00:07:06,499
And there's a very good talk on TED by a man called David Chalmers, a philosopher,

70
00:07:07,069 --> 00:07:18,004
And he's positing that consciousness is actually part and parcel of the universe, just as matter, time, space and all that, and consciousness.

71
00:07:18,605 --> 00:07:25,095
He's very careful not to move into a sort of pantheism, you know, like God is everywhere, anything like that.

72
00:07:25,632 --> 00:07:26,913
He doesn't want to overstep the line.

73
00:07:27,434 --> 00:07:45,233
But in that way, he's saying that consciousness being, as we say, embedded in the whole process of the universe begins at the very base as a sort of proto-consciousness, and it grows.

74
00:07:45,973 --> 00:07:49,057
And this reminds me of a philosopher now.

75
00:07:49,999 --> 00:07:53,682
He's a Jesuit, a Christian philosopher.

76
00:07:53,702 --> 00:07:54,903
He was a paleontologist.

77
00:07:54,923 --> 00:07:55,605
Well, not a paleontologist.

78
00:07:56,259 --> 00:08:15,889
Tyada Shaddam and he had because of his study of skulls and ancient skeletons and all that his word for this growing consciousness was the encephalization of consciousness so as consciousness grew the brain had to grow bigger.

79
00:08:16,442 --> 00:08:26,535
And really we're looking now down upon what we experience, not from below up, from stones upwards, but we're looking down from consciousness.

80
00:08:28,137 --> 00:08:31,380
And we'll see that that gives us a slightly different view of things.

81
00:08:34,725 --> 00:08:41,673
So from the Buddha's perspective, from the Buddha's perspective,

82
00:08:41,840 --> 00:08:47,988
we definitely are made up of three parts.

83
00:08:48,028 --> 00:08:54,277
Our physical nature, which can only be known through the mind at the contact pace.

84
00:08:54,817 --> 00:09:07,755
So when we chant the Dependent Origination in the morning, it's that point of contact where we are, shall we say, touching on the physical nature of the universe.

85
00:09:08,557 --> 00:09:11,019
And when you think about it, it's quite remarkable because

86
00:09:11,219 --> 00:09:14,764
The eyes are actually sensitive to subatomic particles.

87
00:09:15,005 --> 00:09:16,227
It's just absolutely amazing.

88
00:09:17,129 --> 00:09:22,077
And the tongue is sensible to chemicals and things like that.

89
00:09:22,919 --> 00:09:25,303
So there is this point of contact.

90
00:09:25,344 --> 00:09:26,966
But then from that.

91
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:35,216
It's taken into what's known as the mind door, and it's the mind door which figures it all out, which puts it into some sort of definition.

92
00:09:35,535 --> 00:09:40,225
You know, this is curry, or I can hear a car.

93
00:09:40,686 --> 00:09:43,572
At the ear door, all you're getting is pressure.

94
00:09:45,644 --> 00:10:08,715
the airwaves are just pressure everything else is taken back into the mind door and then and from that from that point of recognizing what it is then you give it meaning right so a car begins to have meaning it's a taxi coming for me and all that sort of stuff so all that is mine and there is this third quality of the nirvanic element that's how it's referred to in um

95
00:10:09,758 --> 00:10:16,285
In our school, in later schools of course, they tended to personalise it and call it Buddha nature, things like that.

96
00:10:17,168 --> 00:10:19,350
And that was because there was a shift of emphasis.

97
00:10:20,171 --> 00:10:31,566
So the Buddha himself is very wary of saying it's somebody or something even.

98
00:10:32,067 --> 00:10:38,414
He's much more directed to the actual experience and describing the experience of it.

99
00:10:40,522 --> 00:10:43,306
We'll come to that in a minute.

100
00:10:44,347 --> 00:10:47,432
So that's the first thing about materialism.

101
00:10:49,294 --> 00:11:05,158
It seems to be impossible to connect the physicality of our nature, neurons, chemicals and all that, to the way that we subjectively experience things within ourselves.

102
00:11:05,700 --> 00:11:07,643
There seems to be a divide there.

103
00:11:09,158 --> 00:11:16,307
The next thing, and I want to point out another book here, there's a man called Yuval Harari who's written two books and they're really fantastic.

104
00:11:16,427 --> 00:11:19,110
One's Sapiens and the other one is Homo Deus.

105
00:11:19,130 --> 00:11:24,116
Sapiens is about how we get to this point, the growth of humans.

106
00:11:24,738 --> 00:11:27,721
And Deus, Homo Deus is where we're going to go from here.

107
00:11:27,942 --> 00:11:36,312
And one of his big things is to point out that people are actually spending a lot of money so that we don't die.

108
00:11:37,745 --> 00:11:43,586
He was a matter of research going on to stop us dying.

109
00:11:44,342 --> 00:11:49,591
And one thing I learned from him was this word algorithm, which I thought was a very mystical thing.

110
00:11:50,211 --> 00:11:55,719
I thought, you know, like Google has this amazing algorithm and it can find anything you want in milliseconds.

111
00:11:56,299 --> 00:11:59,784
So I've always presumed it really belonged to the area of mysticism.

112
00:12:00,225 --> 00:12:03,029
But it turns out that an algorithm is actually just a menu.

113
00:12:03,571 --> 00:12:05,854
So baking bread.

114
00:12:06,073 --> 00:12:11,140
So when you put that menu into a machine, then the machine bakes bread for you.

115
00:12:11,162 --> 00:12:12,222
And that's its algorithms.

116
00:12:12,827 --> 00:12:17,932
So that was an enormous point of enlightenment for me.

117
00:12:18,113 --> 00:12:29,845
So once we've understood that, when biologists look at nature now, they see this process of algorithms.

118
00:12:29,945 --> 00:12:36,191
They just see menus just being worked out from the very seed to the plant and so on.

119
00:12:36,831 --> 00:12:42,496
And so the huge question has come up, what purpose in evolution is consciousness?

120
00:12:42,847 --> 00:12:43,948
There was no purpose for it.

121
00:12:44,330 --> 00:12:52,200
Because now we have artificial intelligence that can do everything we can do, thinking-wise, mathematically-wise, much faster and much better.

122
00:12:53,201 --> 00:12:55,124
And they never tire, never get headaches.

123
00:12:55,884 --> 00:13:09,581
So you've got all these amazing machines that we've created, which tell us that there's some mismatch there about thinking about where consciousness is.

124
00:13:10,236 --> 00:13:13,620
I mean, does a machine have consciousness who does all your accounts?

125
00:13:14,561 --> 00:13:17,705
So this has really sort of created a problem for them.

126
00:13:20,567 --> 00:13:26,232
Of course, this goes back to, in our history, right back to the Enlightenment.

127
00:13:26,293 --> 00:13:28,696
So remember the scientific revolution.

128
00:13:29,476 --> 00:13:39,466
If you go back a little bit further, actually, to St. Thomas Aquinas, the...

129
00:13:40,341 --> 00:13:46,750
the Christian theologian, where he determined that animals don't have souls.

130
00:13:46,890 --> 00:13:53,740
That's when Christianity came to a conclusion that, philosophically speaking and all that, animals don't have souls.

131
00:13:53,880 --> 00:13:55,302
Only human beings have souls.

132
00:13:55,783 --> 00:14:00,831
So when we get to Descartes and science, they don't have sensibility.

133
00:14:00,811 --> 00:14:10,360
So in the 17th century, people were experimenting on live animals without any sense of, you know, because even though the animals are screaming, it really wasn't suffering any pain.

134
00:14:11,121 --> 00:14:20,071
And there's this, I get this magazine, The Week, which sort of, you probably know it, it summarizes the news for us.

135
00:14:20,751 --> 00:14:23,195
And it always has a little bit of article about science.

136
00:14:23,715 --> 00:14:25,317
And I kid you not.

137
00:14:25,499 --> 00:14:35,916
One week, a bunch of scientists from somewhere finally discovered or had proven that fish do not feel pain.

138
00:14:36,537 --> 00:14:40,003
The very next week, another bunch of scientists proved that they did.

139
00:14:41,544 --> 00:14:49,618
So, I mean, how you can prove anything which is happening inside us, within our own selves, is a mystery.

140
00:14:50,139 --> 00:14:51,961
And all they're looking at is behaviour.

141
00:14:52,330 --> 00:14:59,302
So, you know, you sort of hit a fish on the head and say, well, look, he didn't do anything, so he can't be suffering.

142
00:14:59,322 --> 00:15:05,552
Anyway, so there's this whole problem as to, I just want to point that out.

143
00:15:05,751 --> 00:15:11,621
It came to me as a great surprise that now evolutionary, in evolutionary theory, they have a problem with,

144
00:15:12,039 --> 00:15:41,371
with where consciousness or why consciousness should be necessary how it evolved from matter for what purpose because it's in terms of algorithms it's just it's just not necessary so um when it comes to uh these sort of views um on the one side remember you've also got the eternalist view so the eternalist view and i'm quoting here from uh a um

145
00:15:41,993 --> 00:16:09,519
commentary which is sometimes clearer sometimes because they're defining things so therein what is an eternalist view that the self and the world are eternal now when the Buddha talks about the world the all he's really only talking about the five khandhas he doesn't go the great thing that I found about the Buddha is that he doesn't go where there's only inference

146
00:16:10,715 --> 00:16:20,166
So that's why there's no supernatural stuff or anything like that unless you consider things like levitation and stuff supernatural.

147
00:16:20,546 --> 00:16:24,210
But he doesn't go beyond what you can actually experience.

148
00:16:24,791 --> 00:16:32,058
And that's why he never talks about what it is that experiences Nibbana because it's a total experience.

149
00:16:32,359 --> 00:16:37,544
In the experience there's nobody there who can tell you about it.

150
00:16:38,206 --> 00:16:40,148
Afterwards you can reflect upon it

151
00:16:40,414 --> 00:16:54,238
But while you're in a state of transcendent Nibbana, then all he can do is talk about what it's like, what it doesn't have, and we'll come to that in a little bit.

152
00:16:54,421 --> 00:17:15,123
So it goes on, it says that this form of view, and this is actually from the scriptures, is a thicket of views, a wilderness of views, a contortion of views, a writhing of views, a fetter of views, a seizure, holding on inclination, hanging on false path, wrong way, wrongness, sectarian guide, inverted seizure.

153
00:17:15,423 --> 00:17:18,646
This is what is called an internal view.

154
00:17:18,666 --> 00:17:22,250
I don't know what an inverted seizure is, I just hope I don't have one.

155
00:17:25,201 --> 00:17:43,310
So on the one side, you have this idea of some sort of that something within us, the mind, the heart, emotions, the body and all that, how we experience ourselves phenomenally, that there's something in it which is eternal, right?

156
00:17:44,184 --> 00:17:51,432
And of course the Buddha is pointing out that that's the great discourse on anatta, not self, that he's asking you to see.

157
00:17:51,894 --> 00:17:55,077
If what you're experiencing is impermanent, how can you possibly be it?

158
00:17:57,079 --> 00:18:00,263
And the other side is what we've just been talking about, this annihilationist view.

159
00:18:00,284 --> 00:18:02,385
So the self and the world will be annihilated.

160
00:18:02,445 --> 00:18:05,430
This again, of course, forms a view, a thicket of...

161
00:18:05,450 --> 00:18:06,530
I must read it, I love it.

162
00:18:06,815 --> 00:18:20,231
a wilderness of view, a contortion of views, a writhing of views, a fetter of views, a seizure, holding on, inclination, hanging on, false path, wrong way, wrongness, sectarian guide, inverted seizure.

163
00:18:21,614 --> 00:18:24,778
It's called annihilationist view.

164
00:18:26,038 --> 00:18:29,383
Does anybody know what?

165
00:18:29,403 --> 00:18:32,366
Anyway, that's this eternalist view.

166
00:18:32,936 --> 00:18:39,964
Now, to support that, you see, there is, of course, this very famous quote.

167
00:18:40,005 --> 00:18:44,570
Everybody knows this quote, but they usually only quote the opening lines of it.

168
00:18:46,173 --> 00:18:51,638
So he says, it's coming from the Udana Sutta, which is a collection of his inspired verses.

169
00:18:52,460 --> 00:18:56,565
And it says, I have heard that on one occasion, this would be Ananda,

170
00:18:56,815 --> 00:19:01,259
The Blessed One was staying near Salvati at Jeta's Grove, an Atipindika's monastery.

171
00:19:01,679 --> 00:19:09,386
And on that occasion, the Blessed One was instructing, urging, rousing and encouraging the monks with Dharma talk, concerned with liberation.

172
00:19:10,047 --> 00:19:15,551
And the monks, receptive, attentive, focusing their entire awareness, lending an ear, listened to the Dharma.

173
00:19:16,053 --> 00:19:21,478
By the way, the commentaries point out that when they use the word monks, they mean anybody who's listening.

174
00:19:21,698 --> 00:19:23,920
It's not just monastics.

175
00:19:26,126 --> 00:19:39,601
Then on realizing the significance of that, the Blessed One on that occasion exclaimed, there is monks are not born and not become and not made and not conditioned.

176
00:19:40,121 --> 00:19:50,592
Now, the way the word is using is a, well, I suppose what we would call a gerund.

177
00:19:50,751 --> 00:19:54,075
It's using an adjective as a noun.

178
00:19:54,847 --> 00:19:59,133
So there is an unborn, not something unborn.

179
00:19:59,272 --> 00:20:07,102
So he's very careful not to again solidify it into some sort of idea of a person or a self.

180
00:20:07,122 --> 00:20:14,250
So he says there is an unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned.

181
00:20:14,910 --> 00:20:17,012
So everything in the world is conditioned.

182
00:20:17,113 --> 00:20:20,797
In other words, everything in the world is dependent on something else for it to arise.

183
00:20:22,198 --> 00:20:24,500
We're dependent on air, for instance.

184
00:20:24,970 --> 00:20:27,073
but this is completely unconditioned.

185
00:20:27,794 --> 00:20:44,315
Then he says, and this is the bit that people don't usually quote, if there were not the unborn, the unbecome, the unmade, the unconditioned, there would be no way of escape from the born, the become, the made, the conditioned.

186
00:20:45,516 --> 00:20:47,117
You could not discern that escape.

187
00:20:48,339 --> 00:20:53,846
And he says precisely because of this, there is an unborn, unbecome, unmade,

188
00:20:54,214 --> 00:20:55,217
And unconditioned.

189
00:20:56,057 --> 00:20:56,960
And this is the escape.

190
00:20:58,462 --> 00:20:59,904
So that's the fullness of the phrase.

191
00:21:00,546 --> 00:21:06,396
So it's very difficult to deny, in my mind, that he's talking about something which is transcendent.

192
00:21:06,978 --> 00:21:10,984
But people do.

193
00:21:12,808 --> 00:21:15,353
That's all you can say.

194
00:21:15,413 --> 00:21:17,978
So that's to do with all this business of transcendence.

195
00:21:19,020 --> 00:21:25,371
annihilation and the reductionism of scientism and stuff.

196
00:21:25,391 --> 00:21:28,236
But he does present us with a further problem.

197
00:21:28,296 --> 00:21:32,561
By the way, in the Buddha's time there were annihilationists.

198
00:21:33,403 --> 00:21:36,028
There was a man called Ajita Kesakambali.

199
00:21:36,608 --> 00:21:40,734
A Lokayata materialist.

200
00:21:40,775 --> 00:21:41,717
So he was a materialist.

201
00:21:42,657 --> 00:21:46,884
And his line was the usual thing that is, you know, on death the body

202
00:21:47,167 --> 00:21:51,996
The body's made of earth, you just return to the earth when you die, so you may as well enjoy life while you can.

203
00:21:52,737 --> 00:22:08,063
And the opening of the first discourse, you know, where he says, he was saying the other week, the opening verse, that sensual pleasure, the seeking of sensual pleasure is one of those extremes that we shouldn't be following, you see.

204
00:22:08,785 --> 00:22:19,346
So if you're a real materialist, if you really, really think that you've only got this life, then really you should be heading for as much enjoyment as you can.

205
00:22:19,486 --> 00:22:24,736
Get as much sex, drugs and rock and roll as you can.

206
00:22:25,436 --> 00:22:25,778
Why not?

207
00:22:27,540 --> 00:22:28,363
So...

208
00:22:29,727 --> 00:22:34,212
And the other side of scientism, of course, is the ethics.

209
00:22:34,614 --> 00:22:37,376
So here's Einstein, believe it or not.

210
00:22:37,396 --> 00:22:39,980
A man's actions are determined by necessity.

211
00:22:40,240 --> 00:22:41,702
It's all conditioned, yeah.

212
00:22:41,722 --> 00:22:43,224
External and internal.

213
00:22:43,645 --> 00:22:52,798
So that in God's eyes, he cannot be responsible any more than an inanimate object is responsible for the motions it goes through.

214
00:22:54,382 --> 00:22:55,963
So we're not at all...

215
00:22:56,305 --> 00:23:08,624
I mean, this actually had great effect in America during the 30s, I think, or something like that, where people got off...

216
00:23:08,683 --> 00:23:10,527
I'm thinking of one particular case.

217
00:23:10,586 --> 00:23:18,599
I was trying to look for it, but I couldn't find it, where a murderer was let off on the grounds that he had no choice.

218
00:23:19,441 --> 00:23:23,327
You know, the conditions that he was in, the way he was brought up, etc., etc.

219
00:23:23,708 --> 00:23:26,854
And he walked free and he just committed murder.

220
00:23:28,457 --> 00:23:29,719
So there's Einstein for you.

221
00:23:29,739 --> 00:23:31,382
It's funny he should talk about God's eyes.

222
00:23:32,963 --> 00:23:38,875
Nietzsche says it in his usual rather roundabout way, but he gets the point across too.

223
00:23:38,894 --> 00:23:44,924
He says, if a man finally succeeds in obtaining philosophical conviction,

224
00:23:45,529 --> 00:24:03,349
of the unconditional necessity of all actions, in other words, conditioned actions, and of their complete irresponsibility, you had to do it, and of getting this into his system, any remnants of pricks of conscience disappear.

225
00:24:04,330 --> 00:24:05,231
Why would you have shame?

226
00:24:05,271 --> 00:24:06,133
Why would you have guilt?

227
00:24:08,915 --> 00:24:10,577
You were forced to pull the man's ears off.

228
00:24:11,097 --> 00:24:12,599
It just happened.

229
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:17,330
Now, of course, in the Buddha's time, you got this similar sort of thing.

230
00:24:17,612 --> 00:24:22,387
You got Makali Gosala, who was a fatalist.

231
00:24:23,818 --> 00:24:27,786
powerless, life was predestined, completely conditioned.

232
00:24:28,567 --> 00:24:29,469
That was his teaching.

233
00:24:30,289 --> 00:24:31,571
And of course that isn't the Buddha's.

234
00:24:31,613 --> 00:24:48,020
The Buddha's is, of course, it's not free will, it's not free will, but our growing discernment tells us that certain actions lead towards suffering and certain actions lead towards happiness and eventually towards release.

235
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:55,432
So we are conditioned, but we're able to change our conditioning through our discernment, through wisdom.

236
00:24:56,093 --> 00:24:58,857
And the change is brought about by an act of will.

237
00:24:58,998 --> 00:25:00,779
So it's a sort of an in-between place.

238
00:25:00,799 --> 00:25:12,337
We're not obviously completely free, but we are free to change our habits because we've created them through this wrong understanding, through acts of will.

239
00:25:13,279 --> 00:25:16,262
The way I describe it is like when you go on a walk.

240
00:25:17,444 --> 00:25:23,131
If you've got a map with you, you get to a point where the road bifurcates and you don't quite know where to go.

241
00:25:23,171 --> 00:25:25,773
So you look at the map and then you see you've got to go right.

242
00:25:26,515 --> 00:25:27,836
So that's the same with us.

243
00:25:29,097 --> 00:25:32,281
The road is, as it were, towards liberation.

244
00:25:34,023 --> 00:25:35,945
Once we're on that road, it's towards liberation.

245
00:25:36,195 --> 00:25:41,183
But there are all sorts of little bypasses and forks and stuff like that where we get occasionally lost.

246
00:25:42,005 --> 00:26:00,634
And it's through discernment, through this reflection, yoniso manesikara, wise reflection, and through our internal experiences where we see, where we come across things like stuff that we've suppressed, little guilts that come up,

247
00:26:00,614 --> 00:26:28,308
um one that came up for me was quite remarkable actually when i was about 18 or 19 i think and it was uh winter and i was coming home driving the old man's car it was one of these great big rovers it's like a tank and as i came round into the street where where we lived uh the street before so you come off the main road you turn right and then you first turn left the car very gently slid across

248
00:26:28,728 --> 00:26:38,338
I got home, you know, and the next morning my mother said, oh, there's been a crash at the road and somebody's knocked the wall over of this neighbour.

249
00:26:39,520 --> 00:26:42,523
And I went out and took the brickwork off the mudguard, you know.

250
00:26:43,945 --> 00:26:45,347
And I said, nothing, you see.

251
00:26:46,249 --> 00:26:51,714
And this is when I'm in my middle 40s.

252
00:26:51,795 --> 00:26:55,038
I'm sitting there sitting and suddenly this...

253
00:26:55,306 --> 00:27:24,267
huge sort of horror arises in me of not having you know of not taking responsibility for it and what might have happened and all that so it's I obviously buried that sense of shock in the system so it's not as though you get away with anything eventually although I don't know he presumably got insured you know he got it on the insurance yeah

254
00:27:25,106 --> 00:27:25,768
Oh, dear me.

255
00:27:28,130 --> 00:27:29,972
Just a little older.

256
00:27:29,992 --> 00:27:35,679
My mother, this is many years on, but my mother came to me and said, one day, she said, somebody's hit the wall.

257
00:27:36,099 --> 00:27:37,280
So I said, oh, I went out there.

258
00:27:37,300 --> 00:27:38,722
Well, I couldn't see it, you see.

259
00:27:39,063 --> 00:27:41,164
She said, yeah, no, no, that's been touched.

260
00:27:41,445 --> 00:27:43,288
There's a brick that's sticking out, you see.

261
00:27:44,169 --> 00:27:47,772
So we got it redone on the insurance side.

262
00:27:49,238 --> 00:27:51,481
I thought, anyway, we've got to be done with the insurance.

263
00:27:51,501 --> 00:27:56,108
And the insurance man came, and he knocked at the door, and he said, it's cost you about 100 quid.

264
00:27:56,368 --> 00:28:01,738
And he said, I can make it 200 and give you 100, you see.

265
00:28:01,798 --> 00:28:02,660
And my mother said, oh.

266
00:28:02,859 --> 00:28:03,340
I said, no.

267
00:28:03,361 --> 00:28:03,882
I said, no, no.

268
00:28:04,182 --> 00:28:05,724
I said, well, play straight.

269
00:28:05,964 --> 00:28:07,426
And she was very angry with me.

270
00:28:09,951 --> 00:28:10,752
Because she was a killer.

271
00:28:13,477 --> 00:28:13,897
Yes.

272
00:28:15,019 --> 00:28:16,561
Anyway, so...

273
00:28:17,790 --> 00:28:19,722
That's definitely not the Buddha's teaching anyway.

274
00:28:19,803 --> 00:28:24,914
He's not into fiddling.

275
00:28:27,140 --> 00:28:36,974
So, he actually talks about shame and guilt as being the guardians of society, the guardian, not the guards, they're not wicked, they're there to tell us.

276
00:28:36,994 --> 00:28:52,219
So, basically, as we become more and more refined and you do something which you feel is hurtful, both to the other or to yourself or to both, then immediately you get that sense of having done something wrong, guilt, right?

277
00:28:52,199 --> 00:28:56,163
This isn't the great existential guilt that I shouldn't be here anyway because I'm so evil.

278
00:28:56,484 --> 00:28:57,767
It's just I did something wrong.

279
00:28:58,346 --> 00:28:59,588
And shame.

280
00:28:59,729 --> 00:29:01,030
You feel a bit ashamed about it.

281
00:29:01,050 --> 00:29:03,173
So you have to put that right to clear the heart, you see.

282
00:29:03,815 --> 00:29:08,701
So in that way, shame and guilt become the guardians of society.

283
00:29:11,464 --> 00:29:18,595
So from a Buddhist point of view,

284
00:29:18,692 --> 00:29:23,859
scientism, in a sense, leads to a sort of dead end, really.

285
00:29:24,621 --> 00:29:38,240
And one thing that would occur to me, I think, you don't know, of course, but it would occur to me that if I were truly a materialist, thinking that, well, you know, at the end of... At some point I'll die and that'll be the end of it.

286
00:29:39,382 --> 00:29:46,873
I can't imagine myself having put so much energy into the practice, especially when it got incredibly difficult.

287
00:29:46,893 --> 00:29:48,295
I would have thought, well...

288
00:29:48,493 --> 00:29:49,537
You know, this is ridiculous.

289
00:29:49,596 --> 00:29:50,900
I might as well go out and have a pint.

290
00:29:52,323 --> 00:29:53,767
Do something useful.

291
00:29:55,912 --> 00:29:57,536
And I think that's a big block.

292
00:29:57,936 --> 00:30:02,267
And of course, these things are self-reinforcing, aren't they?

293
00:30:02,872 --> 00:30:14,164
Because eventually you have to justify the fact that you're not putting a great deal of effort in the practice because, well, life's short and I'm not going to get fully liberated anyway, so what's the point?

294
00:30:14,185 --> 00:30:19,991
I may as well be a little liberated and make my way as best I can.

295
00:30:21,074 --> 00:30:23,997
So in a sense it undermines the great project for us.

296
00:30:24,176 --> 00:30:28,001
It's sort of underselling the Buddha's teachings.

297
00:30:30,326 --> 00:30:37,061
So that's the first area, that's the first avenue in which Buddhism is being received, you see, through science.

298
00:30:37,082 --> 00:30:45,821
And of course we have now this mindfulness movement, which has brought it into medicine and medicine.

299
00:30:46,055 --> 00:31:14,458
mental health and it's being used for that purpose and occasionally somebody actually wants to find out where this comes from so I do get people very occasionally who come from having done mindfulness and stress reduction or something and they've taken it a bit further and although sometimes people criticise it because it's not taught with morality and stuff the fact is you know it

300
00:31:14,624 --> 00:31:17,469
It does people good, so, you know, don't knock it.

301
00:31:18,912 --> 00:31:21,738
That's my own personal opinion, of course.

302
00:31:21,758 --> 00:31:23,520
So now we have Romanticism.

303
00:31:26,727 --> 00:31:30,835
Tanisarovic, whom some of you might know, has written a very good book on it.

304
00:31:32,397 --> 00:31:35,063
And here I just want to pull out one or two things just to show us.

305
00:31:35,498 --> 00:31:46,494
So the Romantic movement was a reaction to the scientific revolution and what we call the Enlightenment, the rise of rationalism.

306
00:31:46,955 --> 00:31:56,329
So you have Newton telling us that everything is just mechanical and God is ex machina, deus ex machina, he's the God outside the machine.

307
00:31:56,549 --> 00:31:59,515
He sort of set it going and let it run.

308
00:31:59,494 --> 00:32:06,373
And then you've got Kant telling us we shouldn't really trust our feelings.

309
00:32:06,432 --> 00:32:07,435
We should be rational.

310
00:32:08,538 --> 00:32:10,604
You know, morality is a rational thing.

311
00:32:11,686 --> 00:32:15,376
We've got Descartes telling us that animals don't have any feelings.

312
00:32:15,356 --> 00:32:16,739
Don't feel anything.

313
00:32:16,759 --> 00:32:21,244
And then there's a sort of reaction against that back to the heart.

314
00:32:21,846 --> 00:32:23,008
So we have it today.

315
00:32:23,048 --> 00:32:26,692
Some people say, well, I feel, meaning I know.

316
00:32:26,732 --> 00:32:29,616
And some people say, I think, meaning I know.

317
00:32:30,117 --> 00:32:32,721
So it depends where you center yourself.

318
00:32:32,740 --> 00:32:36,066
And hopefully for most of us, it's sort of coming together.

319
00:32:37,800 --> 00:32:48,502
So the great philosophers of the Romantic movement were the German, really, the Romantic, the German Romantics, Novalis and Schleiermacher.

320
00:32:49,057 --> 00:32:54,806
And I'm just now reducing everything to the basics of what they taught.

321
00:32:56,347 --> 00:32:58,270
The first thing, of course, was back to nature.

322
00:32:58,832 --> 00:33:07,203
Because what the Industrial Revolution did, of course, was take people out from nature, stick them in these dreadful factories, satanic mills and all that sort of stuff.

323
00:33:07,223 --> 00:33:09,968
And there was that loss of connection with nature.

324
00:33:10,166 --> 00:33:12,009
So therefore a sense of alienation.

325
00:33:12,470 --> 00:33:19,922
And alienation brought about, as described by Marx, by doing things that weren't connected to you.

326
00:33:19,981 --> 00:33:23,006
You were making things that you couldn't even buy.

327
00:33:23,066 --> 00:33:28,334
And life had become very rigid, it wasn't with the seasons.

328
00:33:28,515 --> 00:33:35,365
I remember a woman who came to the Vihara in Birmingham saying that...

329
00:33:35,345 --> 00:33:41,713
there was a point where they brought electricity on the farm and they lost time.

330
00:33:41,773 --> 00:33:49,223
That's how she expressed what happened to her as a young girl, or she might have been a bit older than just a young girl.

331
00:33:49,805 --> 00:33:58,517
So in the old days, say during winter, you'd have this vast amount of darkness and time, you know, where you could, I don't know,

332
00:33:58,497 --> 00:34:20,268
tell stories and stuff like that and suddenly you've got light and you're back up at five o'clock milking cows and and she expressed it as a loss of time so you can see that people being pushed out of the the country into these horrible hovels uh to work in mills and stuff were alienated they felt separate from from the world

333
00:34:21,920 --> 00:34:23,563
a sense of dislocation, you know.

334
00:34:24,103 --> 00:34:45,682
So these people tried to get people back to it and the first thing was the love of nature and of course I'm just quoting Wordsworth here, you see, you know, the very famous, I wandered lonely as a cloud that floats on high or veils and hills when all at once I saw a crowd, a host of golden daffodils beside the lake, beneath the trees, fluttering and dancing

335
00:34:51,804 --> 00:35:01,655
So you see a sort of movement back to nature and with it the feeling that we begin to understand nature as an organic whole.

336
00:35:01,876 --> 00:35:04,784
So this is way before James Lovelock and his Gaia theory.

337
00:35:05,795 --> 00:35:07,476
And we are part of that organic whole.

338
00:35:08,018 --> 00:35:19,452
And the interesting thing is that although there's purpose in the universe, there's no specific purpose for human beings.

339
00:35:19,753 --> 00:35:21,516
They also accepted a lot of science.

340
00:35:21,815 --> 00:35:23,458
They didn't reject science.

341
00:35:24,219 --> 00:35:34,873
So I think a lot of them were atheists, were annihilationists, what we would call annihilationists.

342
00:35:35,409 --> 00:35:48,733
So all they knew was that if you gave yourself to nature, if you went back to nature and meditated and that sense of awe and wonder came, then you would have this experience of oneness, this oceanic feeling.

343
00:35:49,835 --> 00:35:53,722
Freud dismissed that as something coming up from being a baby.

344
00:35:55,119 --> 00:36:01,115
So this getting lost in this oceanic feeling, which was the height of spiritual endeavor.

345
00:36:01,737 --> 00:36:06,070
And through practice, you could make it last a bit longer, but it definitely didn't last forever.

346
00:36:06,250 --> 00:36:07,914
And eventually you died.

347
00:36:08,992 --> 00:36:16,204
So it was the idea that the individual was mirrored in nature and nature was mirrored in the individual.

348
00:36:16,284 --> 00:36:24,155
And the purpose of life was to find that connection and be reintegrated, to lose that sense of separateness.

349
00:36:24,958 --> 00:36:29,625
And that's what you lost when you went into this oceanic feeling of being at one with nature.

350
00:36:31,067 --> 00:36:35,134
I have to say I had a very, for me, a rather strange experience.

351
00:36:35,282 --> 00:36:37,965
I was up in the hills of Sri Lanka.

352
00:36:38,586 --> 00:36:40,949
And I came out of a retreat, a long retreat.

353
00:36:40,969 --> 00:36:42,572
I think I was up there for a couple of months.

354
00:36:43,472 --> 00:36:44,914
And I climbed this hill.

355
00:36:44,974 --> 00:36:51,163
And just the beauty of the landscape was such that I couldn't stop crying.

356
00:36:51,684 --> 00:36:52,764
I was crying my eyes out.

357
00:36:53,565 --> 00:36:56,530
It was almost too painful to be able to see.

358
00:36:57,231 --> 00:36:59,112
And this reminds me of...

359
00:36:59,211 --> 00:37:06,500
A video you can see of Ajaan Mahabua, who has told us he doesn't suffer, he's an Arahant.

360
00:37:06,519 --> 00:37:15,190
And while he's telling people how that moment where he was completely liberated, he remembers the sort of joy, and he can't stop crying.

361
00:37:16,231 --> 00:37:22,057
And this old man, he must be in his 90s, and this old man crying, telling people how wonderful it was.

362
00:37:22,338 --> 00:37:26,063
And of course all these critics say, no Arahant can cry, it's ridiculous, you know what I'm saying.

363
00:37:27,746 --> 00:37:28,949
He lambasts them.

364
00:37:28,969 --> 00:37:34,916
He's written an essay saying, how do you know how to have a response to life and stuff?

365
00:37:36,418 --> 00:37:39,804
So that was it.

366
00:37:39,844 --> 00:37:45,472
The deepest suffering was this feeling of alienation from nature and the evolutionary process.

367
00:37:46,273 --> 00:37:48,597
So they believed in the evolutionary process, the Darwinism.

368
00:37:50,059 --> 00:37:52,202
But it could be alleviated momentarily.

369
00:37:52,739 --> 00:37:53,800
And we can all achieve this.

370
00:37:53,820 --> 00:37:54,762
We can all find our way.

371
00:37:54,802 --> 00:37:56,206
There's no set way to do it.

372
00:37:56,306 --> 00:37:58,811
So there's no particular religion.

373
00:37:59,192 --> 00:38:02,818
You just had to find your way to get lost into this feeling.

374
00:38:02,838 --> 00:38:08,911
Now, the other thing was, of course, again, the ethics tended to be because you were part of that organic whole.

375
00:38:08,931 --> 00:38:10,414
There was no free will.

376
00:38:10,434 --> 00:38:14,561
So the idea that you were making choices and whatnot was a delusion.

377
00:38:16,027 --> 00:38:27,340
So again, we go back to this idea of being completely conditioned without any sense of free will.

378
00:38:28,981 --> 00:38:37,831
Yes, and I was going to, this whole idea of life is about, what we get from the romantics is that life is about experience.

379
00:38:38,992 --> 00:38:50,166
And that comes right through to our liberal society, that what we're working for is experience, for the holiday, for visiting Machu Picchu and the Norwegian fjords.

380
00:38:50,567 --> 00:38:58,416
And if you haven't seen the lights up on the Arctic, then frankly, you haven't lived.

381
00:38:58,836 --> 00:39:01,619
You've got to sort of display your T-shirts.

382
00:39:03,422 --> 00:39:08,307
And so life is about these peak experiences, and we'll come to that in a minute,

383
00:39:09,014 --> 00:39:14,702
And one thing I thought to get you to imagine is, what would you feel?

384
00:39:15,603 --> 00:39:22,693
What would you feel like now, looking at a different life that you've led?

385
00:39:23,373 --> 00:39:30,844
Or should we say, knowing that you could have led a life which was about having various experiences.

386
00:39:34,128 --> 00:39:37,333
So you're a young boy, a young girl,

387
00:39:38,561 --> 00:40:05,615
you're brought up in a village where the routine is just very regular you know going through the various seasons the cold season the hot season the rainy season and then around about the age of eight you decide that you'd like to join a monastery and you join the monastery and you don't play any games and you have times in the day where you do a bit of study and you chant together and you eat together you sleep together and you get up too early and you feel tired

388
00:40:07,181 --> 00:40:09,152
And you just go through year after year.

389
00:40:09,333 --> 00:40:12,909
About the age of 21, you become a monk and you carry on doing the same things.

390
00:40:13,413 --> 00:40:15,302
Sometimes you give a talk, sometimes you don't.

391
00:40:15,721 --> 00:40:20,606
And the bell goes at three o'clock in the morning and you get up and you do a bit of meditation or you wander about a bit.

392
00:40:21,047 --> 00:40:24,012
And then you turn up for breakfast and it's the same old breakfast.

393
00:40:24,052 --> 00:40:24,751
It never changes.

394
00:40:24,793 --> 00:40:28,757
Sometimes you get a delightful something that turns up.

395
00:40:29,038 --> 00:40:34,824
But generally speaking, and then you wander out and it's similar conversations about the weather and all this sort of stuff.

396
00:40:34,844 --> 00:40:37,668
And then you wander back to your hut and you do a bit of meditation.

397
00:40:37,708 --> 00:40:40,092
And then the bell goes for lunch and you get your bowl ready.

398
00:40:40,460 --> 00:40:43,784
And you walk up for your bowl and you get your lunch and then you go back again.

399
00:40:44,445 --> 00:40:49,393
And you might have a kip in the middle of the day and you might read a bit and you might meditate a bit.

400
00:40:49,432 --> 00:40:51,956
You might meet up with people and you go for an evening chanting.

401
00:40:52,498 --> 00:40:54,139
And there's a cup of tea or something, you know.

402
00:40:54,199 --> 00:40:57,786
And then in the evening you do a bit more meditation, do a bit more chanting.

403
00:40:58,206 --> 00:41:01,050
And then you go to sleep and ready to get up again.

404
00:41:01,090 --> 00:41:02,432
Next morning at three o'clock.

405
00:41:02,833 --> 00:41:04,255
Every day, on and on.

406
00:41:04,394 --> 00:41:07,480
And then suddenly you're very old and you get a cough and you drop dead.

407
00:41:10,835 --> 00:41:13,958
Is that a worthwhile life from a romantic point of view?

408
00:41:16,503 --> 00:41:18,105
They've hardly walked up a mountain.

409
00:41:18,164 --> 00:41:19,467
They've never played a game.

410
00:41:20,469 --> 00:41:21,510
They've never got drunk.

411
00:41:21,550 --> 00:41:22,652
They've never had sex.

412
00:41:22,891 --> 00:41:23,552
Oh my God.

413
00:41:24,114 --> 00:41:24,835
Can you imagine that?

414
00:41:25,275 --> 00:41:27,458
Going through life without having had sex.

415
00:41:28,981 --> 00:41:37,092
So you can see when you contrast that with the way we expect to live in a liberal society, it's just completely different.

416
00:41:37,452 --> 00:41:39,255
Just a different aim altogether.

417
00:41:39,521 --> 00:41:45,951
And yet this little boy may become fully liberated and live in eternal bliss.

418
00:41:48,855 --> 00:41:50,836
And will die with tremendous guilt and horror.

419
00:41:52,800 --> 00:41:56,125
So it's something to sort of just contemplate.

420
00:41:57,385 --> 00:42:04,416
How much of our lives are driven by trying to get some sort of what Maslow calls peak experience?

421
00:42:05,391 --> 00:42:08,637
And that's what we come to next, really, the psychotherapy.

422
00:42:09,318 --> 00:42:17,833
So psychotherapy really turns everything into some sort of medical problem.

423
00:42:19,818 --> 00:42:21,320
It's not really a moral problem.

424
00:42:21,940 --> 00:42:28,512
Everything turns into some sort of medical or social problem.

425
00:42:29,269 --> 00:42:35,318
The idea of morality doesn't really figure very highly in most psychotherapies.

426
00:42:36,621 --> 00:42:52,746
So we go back to Freud, who of course, the idea that you had this subconscious, this id, that you didn't know about, and it was constantly coming into consciousness, your ego, and this sort of figure above you, which was society,

427
00:42:53,047 --> 00:43:18,041
what you'd learned trying to guide you and and your job was to try and find a way to to sort of find your way through that morass that was coming at you all the time sort of uncontrollable urges and this and the voice of god uh coming down upon you um i mean i'm being flippant of course and then you've got people like carl your earth power alfred adler thought it was all about power

428
00:43:18,780 --> 00:43:26,393
Carl Jung, of course, went a little bit deeper, I think, into all this universal consciousness and stuff.

429
00:43:27,153 --> 00:43:32,501
Then you get a break from that with behaviorism, where people like Skinner only looked at your behavior.

430
00:43:33,043 --> 00:43:35,867
And the whole idea of an internal life just went by the board.

431
00:43:37,590 --> 00:43:42,476
And it was all about conditioning, trying to condition people.

432
00:43:43,164 --> 00:43:54,153
And he had some very horrible ideas about bringing up children and making them do things, conditioning them, definitely not giving them love, that would make them soft.

433
00:43:54,403 --> 00:44:13,407
And then there was the great Dr. Spock in the 60s, the American psychologist, the damn doctor I think he was, who brought out this book which has sold millions, I mean 50 millions, it's still in print, where he actually says parents should trust themselves and they should love their baby.

434
00:44:13,675 --> 00:44:15,498
and I'll try and train it and stuff.

435
00:44:15,518 --> 00:44:17,782
Yeah, if you read about it, it's all very strange.

436
00:44:18,181 --> 00:44:25,012
Like, huge swings within that, within the whole process, the whole development of psychotherapy.

437
00:44:25,454 --> 00:44:31,322
But the one I want to point out is Maslow, because Maslow is a humanist psychotherapist.

438
00:44:31,764 --> 00:44:37,713
Maslow looked at people who were having a good time, right, instead of people who had issues.

439
00:44:38,856 --> 00:44:40,998
And he talks, and the thing I want to point out to you is this,

440
00:44:40,978 --> 00:44:42,981
This peak experience.

441
00:44:43,001 --> 00:44:49,726
So when somebody has a peak experience, all these things seemingly happen at the same time.

442
00:44:51,708 --> 00:44:54,652
There's a loss of the judgment to time and space.

443
00:44:54,711 --> 00:44:56,673
So you lose a sense of time and space.

444
00:44:57,273 --> 00:45:02,398
There's a feeling of being one whole and harmonious self, free of dissociation or inner conflict.

445
00:45:03,400 --> 00:45:08,505
A feeling of using all capacities and capabilities at the highest potential of being fully functioning.

446
00:45:09,159 --> 00:45:38,086
functioning effortlessly and easily without strain or struggle, feeling completely responsible for perceptions and behaviour, the use of self-determination to become stronger, more single-minded, fully volitional, being without inhibition, fear, doubt or self-criticism, spontaneous, expressiveness, naturally flowing behaviour that is not constrained by conformity, a free mind that is flexible and open to creative thoughts and ideas,

447
00:45:38,606 --> 00:45:44,836
Complete mindfulness of the present moment without influence of past or expected future experiences.

448
00:45:45,538 --> 00:45:53,750
A physical feeling of warmth along with sensation of pleasant vibrations emanating from the heart area outwards into the limbs.

449
00:45:54,452 --> 00:45:54,731
Wow.

450
00:45:57,556 --> 00:46:00,740
Sounds very Arahatship, I think.

451
00:46:01,322 --> 00:46:06,230
So at least there's a movement there to point to something which is of a higher order.

452
00:46:06,409 --> 00:46:07,010
But again...

453
00:46:07,597 --> 00:46:13,806
It's all to do with the mind, it's all to do with feeling, it's all to do with the way you think, the way you function.

454
00:46:14,806 --> 00:46:21,695
There's no hint here of anything that might be transcendent of that.

455
00:46:24,858 --> 00:46:29,505
It's not as though psychotherapy is against psychology.

456
00:46:30,159 --> 00:46:31,382
what we're doing, the pasana.

457
00:46:31,842 --> 00:46:33,463
It's just there's a different aim.

458
00:46:33,625 --> 00:46:56,454
So psychotherapy, generally speaking, as I understand it, is about finding an accommodation to life, working with difficult situations, like you get marriage counselling and stuff like that, and trying to work out, trying to work through mental states that we're suffering from, panic and depression and all that sort of stuff.

459
00:46:56,434 --> 00:47:01,440
And in that, of course, it's very successful and very helpful.

460
00:47:02,360 --> 00:47:12,911
In the East, you see, if you get very, very depressed or you have things like panic attack, then you might go to a monastery and they'll just tell you to practice metta.

461
00:47:14,833 --> 00:47:20,400
There's not much in Buddhist teaching that I've come across anyway.

462
00:47:20,735 --> 00:47:24,539
which is to do with helping people with severe mental problems.

463
00:47:25,079 --> 00:47:26,822
And it would all be put down to karma.

464
00:47:27,161 --> 00:47:39,376
And the fact that, you know, well, this life you're bearing the karma of what you did wrong in the last life, so don't worry, when you die you'll be born somewhere else and you'll be much happier.

465
00:47:39,396 --> 00:47:46,103
So there's this idea of that because you're suffering something from some past action.

466
00:47:48,327 --> 00:47:49,407
So...

467
00:47:51,228 --> 00:47:55,996
It's really looking at the world from a different angle if we're going to look at it spiritually.

468
00:47:56,396 --> 00:48:09,760
So instead of looking bottom up through the physical nature and then up and up and up and thinking that everything arises out of that, if you look down, coming down from, say, this transcendent experience,

469
00:48:10,010 --> 00:48:12,614
then you get a different thing altogether.

470
00:48:12,954 --> 00:48:15,177
And again, lots of stuff is inexplicable.

471
00:48:15,257 --> 00:48:24,349
For instance, the process of rebirth, the process of how you move from one place to another upon death, is not described in the scriptures.

472
00:48:24,750 --> 00:48:32,701
It's talked about, it's spoken, it's actually said that this is what happens, but the actual process is not described.

473
00:48:33,001 --> 00:48:38,969
So there's lots of areas which are just left probably to our imaginations.

474
00:48:40,030 --> 00:48:58,427
So the first one, the first very famous, again, statement by the Buddhist, it's considered his clearest statement of the Nibbanic experience or of Nibbana, is this one again from the Udana Sutta, which is the collection of his inspired verses.

475
00:48:59,188 --> 00:49:06,375
So again, Ananda says, I have heard that on one occasion the Blessed One was staying near Sarvati, same place, at Jeta's Grove.

476
00:49:06,414 --> 00:49:09,818
It was his favourite monastery, an Atapindika's monastery,

477
00:49:10,269 --> 00:49:17,005
And on that occasion, the Blessed One was instructing, urging, rousing and encouraging monks with Dharma talk concerned with liberation.

478
00:49:17,547 --> 00:49:24,262
And the monks, receptive, attentive, focusing their attention, lending an ear, listened to the Dharma.

479
00:49:24,842 --> 00:49:28,751
And on realising the significance of this, the Buddha on that occasion exclaimed...

480
00:49:29,170 --> 00:49:32,994
So there is a dimension, there is a sphere amongst.

481
00:49:33,713 --> 00:49:43,023
Now remember this word ayatana, you chant it every morning in dependent origination, there's salayatana, the six sense spheres.

482
00:49:43,643 --> 00:49:49,809
And the thing about spheres is that you can't mix them, so you can't hear through your eyes, for instance.

483
00:49:50,110 --> 00:49:53,753
So they are distinct experiences, the ayatana.

484
00:49:54,855 --> 00:49:57,878
A word here, dimension, is rather nice.

485
00:49:58,313 --> 00:49:59,699
and uh...

486
00:50:02,887 --> 00:50:05,411
What he's saying is that there is this dimension.

487
00:50:05,672 --> 00:50:12,163
So this isn't something, shall we say, this isn't poetry, this isn't a metaphor.

488
00:50:12,643 --> 00:50:20,177
He's actually using the same word that he uses for what we experience through the senses, the sixth senses, the sixth being the mind.

489
00:50:21,259 --> 00:50:28,371
So there is, and again the word atti, there's two words in Pali, and I should have mentioned that with the earlier words.

490
00:50:28,351 --> 00:50:29,251
A quote that I gave.

491
00:50:29,532 --> 00:50:31,195
There are two words in Pali for is.

492
00:50:31,717 --> 00:50:33,960
One is what you call a copulative.

493
00:50:34,742 --> 00:50:39,168
It's like when you say this is a table or this is an electric fire.

494
00:50:39,710 --> 00:50:41,452
It's just something to join two words.

495
00:50:41,693 --> 00:50:42,954
And the word for that is hoti.

496
00:50:44,297 --> 00:50:48,384
But when you say is to mean exists, then the word is ati.

497
00:50:48,403 --> 00:50:52,030
So when they ask the Buddha, does the Tathagata exist ati?

498
00:50:52,364 --> 00:50:55,230
When he, you know, after he dies or does he not exist, etc.

499
00:50:55,250 --> 00:50:57,034
The word is ati, right?

500
00:50:57,054 --> 00:50:58,255
So this is the word he uses here.

501
00:50:58,275 --> 00:50:59,659
He says there is a dimension.

502
00:51:00,942 --> 00:51:04,268
Now he says where there's neither earth, water, nor fire, nor wind.

503
00:51:04,630 --> 00:51:06,974
So again, nothing of the physical world.

504
00:51:07,114 --> 00:51:11,925
But again, he doesn't go beyond what we can sense of the physical world.

505
00:51:12,327 --> 00:51:25,492
So remember, these are referring to qualities, to pressure, fluidity, some sort of temperature and movement.

506
00:51:26,873 --> 00:51:46,342
Then he says there's neither the dimension, neither the same sphere, because that's also called a sphere, of these higher jhanas, the four arupa jhanas, the infinitude of space, infinitude of consciousness, the dimension of nothingness, and the place of perception or non-perception.

507
00:51:46,362 --> 00:51:53,552
So even the highest level that you can take the mind to in its most refined state is not there.

508
00:51:53,753 --> 00:51:55,074
That's not what he's talking about.

509
00:51:55,661 --> 00:51:58,190
And he said it's neither of this world nor the next world.

510
00:51:58,349 --> 00:52:03,606
And now he's being more physical in the sense by saying there's no sun nor moon.

511
00:52:04,208 --> 00:52:09,385
So it's something completely transcendent other than, right, other than.

512
00:52:10,327 --> 00:52:14,853
And there is, I say, there's neither coming nor going nor staying.

513
00:52:15,353 --> 00:52:16,295
So there's no time.

514
00:52:16,454 --> 00:52:17,275
There's no space.

515
00:52:18,177 --> 00:52:20,599
There's no passing away nor arising.

516
00:52:20,719 --> 00:52:23,844
So there's nothing there which is transient.

517
00:52:23,864 --> 00:52:30,052
And in fact, there's nothing there from this side of experience.

518
00:52:30,072 --> 00:52:31,494
He says it's not fixed.

519
00:52:31,554 --> 00:52:32,496
It's not moving.

520
00:52:32,556 --> 00:52:34,878
And it's not evolving.

521
00:52:34,938 --> 00:52:37,481
Nothing's happening there.

522
00:52:38,271 --> 00:52:40,235
And he says it's without support.

523
00:52:40,336 --> 00:52:42,621
In other words, it's not conditioned.

524
00:52:42,661 --> 00:52:44,626
It's not dependent on anything else.

525
00:52:46,851 --> 00:52:49,076
And he said just this is the end of suffering.

526
00:52:49,096 --> 00:52:56,532
So that's a really clear statement of something which is utterly transcendent of what we normally experience.

527
00:52:57,509 --> 00:53:00,173
And of course, that's what we are backing into.

528
00:53:00,775 --> 00:53:10,653
See, every time you're practicing meditation and you're observing something, you're turning it into an object, which means that the subject, this sense of the observer, is coming back.

529
00:53:11,135 --> 00:53:15,782
It's moving backwards towards a cliff, right?

530
00:53:15,802 --> 00:53:17,226
And the cliff happens to be a great place.

531
00:53:17,626 --> 00:53:18,268
So...

532
00:53:20,155 --> 00:53:28,646
And that's the same word atti is used for the earlier quote that I gave about the unborn, the unmade, the unconditioned.

533
00:53:30,228 --> 00:53:39,159
So we have a theory within Buddhism called the Tathagatagarbha theory, Yogacara, it's called the Yogacara school.

534
00:53:39,983 --> 00:53:51,760
So here the idea is, or the concept is that the Tathagata, the Buddha within, finds itself within a psychophysical organism.

535
00:53:51,920 --> 00:53:55,146
It doesn't necessarily have to be a human.

536
00:53:55,166 --> 00:53:57,809
And it doesn't have any mass, remember.

537
00:53:58,490 --> 00:53:59,612
Nibbana doesn't have any mass.

538
00:54:00,072 --> 00:54:00,713
There's no earth.

539
00:54:01,755 --> 00:54:07,324
So it's as comfortable in a little microbe as it is in an elephant.

540
00:54:08,012 --> 00:54:09,155
Or a dinosaur.

541
00:54:09,697 --> 00:54:10,719
It just fills it.

542
00:54:10,820 --> 00:54:11,802
It's just there with it.

543
00:54:12,905 --> 00:54:24,856
So this finds itself in there and makes this mistake, of course, of believing itself to be this and the urge to seek happiness, the urge to seek liberation.

544
00:54:24,989 --> 00:54:35,460
either impelled from within some sort of intuitive idea that there must be something beyond, or just from living in the world where suffering arises.

545
00:54:35,880 --> 00:54:37,121
They're always trying to escape suffering.

546
00:54:37,561 --> 00:54:43,268
And then when you realise there's pleasures about, and you're happy when there's pleasures about, then of course you seek more pleasure.

547
00:54:44,248 --> 00:54:47,231
For me it's a very straightforward psychological dynamic.

548
00:54:47,251 --> 00:54:53,257
I don't think there's anything too stressful about understanding that.

549
00:54:54,722 --> 00:55:05,090
But then, because of that process, this tatag, this garba, this embryo, begins to grow and eventually end up as the tatagata.

550
00:55:05,110 --> 00:55:07,094
Tatagata means...

551
00:55:07,311 --> 00:55:33,335
it's best translated the basic words mean either thus come or thus gone um but the best translation is of course that he's pointing to something beyond and he uses other imageries like the island so it's when he talks about himself referring to the targeter he's talking about something that has that is transcended right that has transcended so um

552
00:55:34,614 --> 00:55:43,014
How this came about, how the phenomenal universe came about, is never discussed.

553
00:55:44,338 --> 00:55:50,952
All the Buddha points to is that we're here and we're in a mess and he knows how to get us out of the mess.

554
00:55:51,659 --> 00:55:55,626
So it's a very sort of restricted teaching.

555
00:55:56,067 --> 00:55:57,228
He doesn't go beyond that.

556
00:55:57,268 --> 00:56:00,655
He doesn't really talk about physics or biology or anything like that.

557
00:56:00,976 --> 00:56:02,719
It's not in his purview.

558
00:56:02,778 --> 00:56:04,481
It's not what he's actually on about.

559
00:56:05,043 --> 00:56:07,947
He sees clearly through the Four Noble Truths when he states it.

560
00:56:07,967 --> 00:56:12,856
This is an unsatisfactory situation.

561
00:56:13,393 --> 00:56:17,818
And that the problem is how do we get out of that?

562
00:56:17,958 --> 00:56:19,481
Is there an escape from that?

563
00:56:19,900 --> 00:56:20,862
And that's what he discovers.

564
00:56:21,163 --> 00:56:24,206
So his whole teaching is sort of wedged towards this escape.

565
00:56:25,547 --> 00:56:28,170
So lots of things are not explained.

566
00:56:29,693 --> 00:56:33,856
Lots of things are not scientific in the way that we would like them to be.

567
00:56:34,418 --> 00:56:38,463
So the whole idea of rebirth, the whole idea of Nibbana is unscientific.

568
00:56:38,483 --> 00:56:40,465
You're never going to prove it.

569
00:56:42,503 --> 00:57:07,768
So eventually it does boil down to a certain confidence that he wasn't having his own and then to sort of put effort into the practice and just begin to see even at the level of the role of desire that there is an escape at the point of desire that you don't have to follow this and that you can actually move your whole conditioning towards which is something more beneficial.

570
00:57:14,599 --> 00:57:43,105
so that's about it i think so you've got these um uh three uh ways that we look at something that's coming towards us something new from outside our culture you know we have a we we try to make it fit into our science we try to make it fit into this background idea a romantic view of life of what life's actually about um it has to fit in some way into our psychotherapy and um

571
00:57:43,961 --> 00:58:04,349
Once we're clear as to where all these three things are and where the Buddhist teaching is actually, shall we say, isolated within that, the clarity of the Buddhist teaching, we gaining the clarity of the Buddhist teaching, then of course our progress is going to be much better.

572
00:58:04,469 --> 00:58:05,751
We won't be sidelined.

573
00:58:06,996 --> 00:58:14,730
We won't need, we'll feel that we don't need to come to conclusions.

574
00:58:16,072 --> 00:58:17,994
If we don't know, why come to a conclusion?

575
00:58:19,637 --> 00:58:27,349
I was on a train recently, last year, going down to Brighton, and a rugby crowd got on.

576
00:58:28,072 --> 00:58:32,137
And these two guys opposite me, and one of them said, you're a Buddhist monk, aren't you?

577
00:58:32,157 --> 00:58:33,239
And I said, I am.

578
00:58:33,288 --> 00:58:36,010
He said, well, I don't believe in rebirth or reincarnation.

579
00:58:36,612 --> 00:58:43,278
I said, do you know whether there's reincarnation or not?

580
00:58:43,619 --> 00:58:44,260
And he said, no.

581
00:58:44,760 --> 00:58:46,222
I said, well, why make a conclusion?

582
00:58:46,322 --> 00:58:50,646
And his mate said, yeah, why make a conclusion?

583
00:58:50,666 --> 00:58:53,230
And he just decided there's no such thing as reincarnation.

584
00:58:54,050 --> 00:58:55,632
And we had a great old conversation.

585
00:58:56,204 --> 00:59:02,429
He still didn't believe in it, of course, but at least I might have halted his... Well, it's pride, isn't it?

586
00:59:02,530 --> 00:59:04,251
It's all hubris, you know, like, I know.

587
00:59:04,311 --> 00:59:06,853
It doesn't make sense to me, so it can't be.

588
00:59:07,914 --> 00:59:20,525
So as long as we remain in that sort of humble place, meaning truthful to ourselves, don't know, then we leave open possibility of exploration, possibility of insight.

589
00:59:22,586 --> 00:59:23,327
So there we are.

590
00:59:23,347 --> 00:59:26,110
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

591
00:59:26,748 --> 00:59:30,719
If not, I'm sure you'll leave me a couple of notes.

592
00:59:31,701 --> 00:59:38,579
I can only hope that by your devotion to the practice you may be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

